WOW!<br><br>
The &quot;Jane Fonda&quot; in the title of this thread really caught my attention. <br><br>
Checking it out, all I see are guys having a free-for-all on the issue of &quot;war crimes&quot; by GI's. <br><br>
What really amazes me is that with our prisons full of people who kill, torture, maim, rape, and mutilate without any provocation, motivation, or purpose whatever, people can still focus on what happened with civilians in the Vietnam War, and try to place blame.<br><br>
What I do not see is a similar fury and indignation over what the &quot;civilians&quot; did to GI's in that war.<br><br>
I distinctly remember seeing Mama-san hooch maids pacing off the coordinates to our command bunker from reference points in Lai Khe. The 122's that shortly followed were just about dead on.<br><br>
I distinctly remember the guys who were blown away by the frags tied behind the trays in the 8/6 ARTY mess hall.<br><br>
etc, etc, etc.<br><br>
Remember, these &quot;civilians&quot; were around because they were &quot;checked out&quot; and some bird brained brass decided it was a good thing to do. The 122's or frags did not just materialize out of mess hall swill buckets.<br><br>
Just a little fallout from &quot;pacification&quot;? HA!<br><br>
Is there justification in making a national spectacle about civilian casualties in war, where all activity is devoted to killing, as opposed to minor headlines in the back page press of a local unpremeditated drive-by murder or two?<br><br>
Civilian casualties are horrible and tragic, but are unavoidable in war, regardless of the cause or who did it. Vietnam was no exception. The last I checked, we were trained to kill and sent there to kill. Some Vietnam Vets have had enough problems dealing with the reality of combat without a tangential burden manufactured by someone's distorted sense of values.<br><br>
As far as Jane Fonda is concerned, her treason was a far worse crime against humanity than anything I have seen. She did it to her own people!  <br><br>
  
